Four millions of South Africans mini-bus taxis are their only means of transport. Courtesy #DStv403 * Week-In-One articles examine the top stories of the week from all the angles you may have missed. Watch Week-in-One all weekend on DStv403. JOHANNESBURG - Public transport users say they’re waiting for the government to make good on its promise to provide random screening and sanitisers at all platforms. eNCA spoke with commuters who are vulnerable to the spread of the coronavirus. READ: COVID-19 regulations explained The SA taxi industry alone transports more than 16-million passengers a day.
Hygiene standards leave much to be desired on a normal day and in these abnormal times, they are leading to widespread anxiety. Small business owners have stated they cannot afford to stay at home. Transport Minister Fikile Mbalula said mass education about the novel coronavirus will be provided to commuters as well as increased measures to facilitate hygiene in public transport. The government is working with taxi associations to facilitate deep-cleaning of the vehicles and education at taxi ranks. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.